Effect of recent divergence - dispersal

Larval type – Planktotrophic/pelagic larvae leads to less CS/NS)?

Note1: for this I’m working with a separate surveylarv input file where I have corrected larval types to pt, lt, dd, and removed all others, including cases where there are multiple types checked. (Most of those cases are where the two CS have different larvae.) This left 59 CS with larval info.

Note2: the data fail the homoscedasticity test (Bartlett’s) so I’ve used a nonparametric Kruskal-Wallis test to see if CS/NS is different among groups.

##       DD       LT       PT 
## 3.777778 2.571429 3.023256
##        DD        LT        PT 
## 2.9907264 0.7867958 1.8320997
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  as.numeric(larv_NbCS$Nb_CS) and larv_NbCS$Larv_type
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 0.24525, df = 2, p-value = 0.8846

Hypothesis not supported.

In sum, NO support for the role of recent divergence as measured by a proxy of dispersal when considering only the annelids.

Stabilizing selection

More stable environments = more CSss or statistical differences

Note: stable = pelagic, deepsea, cave, coralreef; not stable = coastal, intertidal, estuarine, seagrass

##         FALSE TRUE

## CSsl_total 0.2432432 0.3846154

Result: Hypothesis not supported; no differences.

Note also that stabilizing selection predicts more CSss than CSsl, which is what we find (see above).

In sum, we generally have some support for this idea.

Results: The results are significant when considering 3 classes, with more no-diff at higher HKK values and more statistical at lower values, but when considering just ss vs sl, difference goes away. So, overall, hypothesis not supported.

In sum, we do not see support for the neutral hypothesis in the annelids.

So, overall conclusions: much like the cnidarians, there’s not support for very much here. Might be because of low sample size but might ALSO be because there’s just really high percentages of CS in this group (Cnidarians and Annelids are among the highest percentage) so we can’t pick out a signal beyond that.
